<!doctype html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>Interview Thesis Brief | Universal Orlando AI Technology</title><link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css"></head><body class="document-body"><nav class="document-nav no-print"><a class="nav-name" href="index.html">Russell Dudek <span>/ Candidate Vision</span></a><div class="doc-actions"><a class="btn primary" href="docs/Russell-Dudek-Universal-Orlando-AI-Interview-Brief.pdf" download>Download PDF</a><button class="btn" onclick="window.print()">Print</button></div></nav><main class="document-shell"><section class="report-page report-title"><div class="report-inner"><div class="report-lockup"><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"><span class="report-label">Independent candidate brief by Russell Dudek</span></div><h1>Interview Thesis Brief</h1><p class="deck">A role-specific point of view for the Director, Artificial Intelligence Technology opportunity.</p><div class="thesis">The model is not the show. The guest experience is.</div><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | Interview thesis brief</span><span>1</span></footer></div></section>
<section class="report-page"><div class="report-inner"><header class="report-header"><h1>01 | Company moment and actual mandate</h1><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"></header><section class="report-section"><h2>The company moment</h2><p>Universal Orlando now presents a four-park destination after Epic Universe opened with five immersive worlds. Reuters reported that the expansion doubled the resort footprint by adding 750 acres and represented an estimated $7 billion investment. Universal Destinations &amp; Experiences describes its portfolio as technologically advanced and continues to expand experience formats and markets.</p><div class="callout">Inference: the AI director enters an environment where more guest journeys, operating systems, data flows, digital products, vendors and always-on dependencies increase both the opportunity for AI and the cost of weak production discipline.</div><h2>The actual mandate</h2><p>Turn distributed AI demand into a governed technical portfolio that produces reliable, adopted and measurable enterprise services - not isolated models. The director must combine strategy, architecture, data and model quality, MLOps, testing, staffing, vendor/API management, responsible AI, executive communication and business ownership.</p><h2>Operating tensions</h2><div class="report-grid-2"><div class="report-card"><h3>Experience vs risk</h3><p>The best technology disappears into immersion; the risk must remain visible to operators.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Speed vs assurance</h3><p>Opportunity moves fast; privacy, safety, security, testing and governance cannot be bolted on later.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Standard vs local</h3><p>Platforms and controls need common architecture while park, hotel, digital and operating workflows retain domain judgment.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Build vs partner</h3><p>Vendors can accelerate delivery, but Universal must retain ownership, observability, resilience and exit paths.</p></div></div></section><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | Interview thesis brief</span><span>2</span></footer></div></section>
<section class="report-page"><div class="report-inner"><header class="report-header"><h1>02 | Candidate thesis and operating model</h1><img src="assets/brand/universal-orlando-logo.png" alt="Universal Orlando Resort"></header><section class="report-section"><h2>Candidate thesis</h2><div class="callout">Build AI so it becomes invisible in the moment - and legible in the operation.</div><p>The proposed AI Show Contract uses four operating books that must agree before an AI capability is treated as production-ready:</p><div class="report-grid-2"><div class="report-card"><h3>Scene</h3><p>Named guest or business outcome, operating owner, baseline, workflow and adoption burden.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Cue</h3><p>Data context, model role and limits, human authority, override, escalation and decision records.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Run</h3><p>SIT, E2E, regression and performance testing; MLOps, observability, drift, latency, security, rollback and vendor resilience.</p></div><div class="report-card"><h3>Review</h3><p>Adoption, ROI, trust, incidents, learning and a disposition to release, revise, reuse, hold or retire.</p></div></div><h2>Decision architecture</h2><p>The director should make these decisions easier: which workflows change; where humans retain authority; build, buy, partner or reuse; what evidence warrants production; what becomes a standard; what is held or stopped; and who owns recovery.</p><h2>Balanced scorecard</h2><p>Guest outcome, flow, economics, run-state health, trust, adoption and learning speed should appear in one portfolio review. A technically healthy model without retained use is not value. A popular workflow without controls is not readiness.</p></section><footer class="page-footer"><span>Russell Dudek | Interview thesis brief</span><span>3</span></footer></div></section>
